C3(1)TAg mouse model dataset visual analysis

Angel F. Alvarado Velez

2025-07-18

What is a C3(1)TAg mouse model?

The C3(1)TAg mouse model is a transgenic mouse model used to study mammary cancer. Its characterized by the expression of the SV40 large T-antigen under the control of the C3(1) gene promoter, leading to tumor development in mammary glands and prostate in male mice. This model is particularly useful for studying basal-like triple-negative breast cancer and the role of obesity in breast cancer development.



1. First we load the necessary libraries

library(Seurat)
library(ggplot2)
library(Seurat)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

2. Run commands to reduce differentiation

seuratObj <- RunPCA(seuratObj)
seuratObj <- NormalizeData(seuratObj)
seuratObj <- FindVariableFeatures(seuratObj)
seuratObj <- ScaleData(seuratObj)
seuratObj <- RunUMAP(seuratObj, dims = 1:10)



Both UMAP & PCA simplify complex data by reducing the number of variables while retaining important information



Visualizations

3. Create UMAP plot side-by-side with annotations for stromalClass and celltype

DimPlot(seuratObj, reduction = "umap", group.by = "stromalClass") + 
  ggtitle("UMAP by Stromal Class") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, vjust = -2))

DimPlot(seuratObj, reduction = "umap", group.by = "celltype") + 
  ggtitle("UMAP by Cell Type") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, vjust = -2))

4. Now, we use FeaturePlot in order to create UMAP projections showing the expressions of 3 genes:

FeaturePlot(seuratObj, features = "Ptn", reduction = "umap")

FeaturePlot(seuratObj,features = "Pecam1", reduction = "umap")

FeaturePlot(seuratObj, features = "Acta2", reduction = "umap")

5, Create a Vln & DotPlot to show distributions of gene expression levels across cell types (Ptn,Acta2 & Pecam1)

VlnPlot(seuratObj, features = c("Ptn", "Pecam1", "Acta2"), group.by = "celltype", pt.size =0.3)

DotPlot(seuratObj, features = c("Ptn", "Pecam1", "Acta2"), group.by = "celltype")

6. Identify marker genes, filter table to top 5 gene markers for each cell type & rearrange table

markers <- FindAllMarkers(seuratObj)
## Warning: The `slot` argument of `GetAssayData()` is deprecated as of SeuratObject 5.0.0.
##  Please use the `layer` argument instead.
##  The deprecated feature was likely used in the Seurat package.
##   Please report the issue at <https://github.com/satijalab/seurat/issues>.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
top_markers <- markers %>%
  group_by(cluster) %>%              
  top_n(5, wt = avg_log2FC) %>%                    
  arrange(cluster, desc(avg_log2FC))
top_markers <- top_markers %>%
  select(c(6, 7, everything()))  # Move columns 6 and 7 to the front**

7. Convert cell type to a factor & drop unused levels 

seuratObj$celltype <- factor(seuratObj$celltype)
seuratObj$celltype <- droplevels(seuratObj$celltype)

8. Create DotPlot showing expression of top cell type marker genes
